as the attachment site for the triceps brachii muscle.","It is located inferiorly on the humerus and serves as the attachment site for the brachialis muscle.","It is located anteriorly on the humerus and serves as the attachment site for the biceps brachii muscle."],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater tubercle\u003C/strong\u003E is an important anatomical landmark on the proximal humerus. Located on its lateral aspect, this bony prominence provides attachment for three of the four rotator cuff muscles: supraspinatus superiorly, infraspinatus posteriorly, and teres minor inferiorly. These muscles work together to stabilise the glenohumeral joint and assist in shoulder movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options describe incorrect anatomical relationships:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edeltoid muscle\u003C/strong\u003E attaches to its own distinct area - the deltoid tuberosity on the lateral humeral shaft\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etriceps brachii muscle\u003C/strong\u003E has its distal attachment on the ulna at the olecranon process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachialis muscle\u003C/strong\u003E attaches to the ulnar tuberosity and coronoid process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiceps brachii muscle\u003C/strong\u003E has its distal attachment at the radial tuberosity, with some fibres forming the bicipital aponeurosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The greater tubercle of the humerus is a prominent area of bone located laterally on the humerus.","It serves as the attachment site for the rotator cuff muscles, including the supraspinatus, infraspinatus, and teres minor.","Understanding the anatomy of the greater tubercle is crucial for diagnosing shoulder injuries and planning surgical interventions."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67737"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18053"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67737","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67737"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T23:30:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T23:31:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10767"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82572"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"he